{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GjdBiJPcqaDaGnuThYZNrH","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Installation\n     2→\n     3→This document covers the various ways to install Cloche on your machine.\n     4→\n     5→## Prerequisites\n     6→\n     7→All installation methods require:\n     8→\n     9→- **Docker** — Cloche runs workflows in containers\n    10→- **Git** — result extraction uses git worktrees\n    11→- **`ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`** — for agent steps using Claude Code\n    12→\n    13→For building from source, you also need:\n    14→\n    15→- **Go 1.25.3+** — matching the version in `go.mod`\n    16→\n    17→Note: Node.js and npm are only needed *inside* the container image (for Claude\n    18→Code). You do **not** need to install them on the host — the Docker image build\n    19→handles this automatically.\n    20→\n    21→## Architecture: What Runs Where\n    22→\n    23→Understanding which components run on the host vs inside containers helps\n    24→clarify what you need to install:\n    25→\n    26→| Component | Where it runs | Notes |\n    27→|---|---|---|\n    28→| `cloche` (CLI) | Host | Sends commands to the daemon over gRPC |\n    29→| `cloched` (Daemon) | Host | Manages container lifecycle and state |\n    30→| `cloche-agent` | Inside containers only | Built into the `cloche-agent:latest` Docker image |\n    31→\n    32→You only need `cloche` and `cloched` on your host. The `cloche-agent` binary is\n    33→compiled into the Docker image during `make docker-build` and never needs to be\n    34→installed on the host.\n    35→\n    36→## Build from Source\n    37→\n    38→Clone the repository, build the binaries and Docker image, and install them:\n    39→\n    40→```\n    41→git clone https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche.git\n    42→cd cloche\n    43→make install\n    44→```\n    45→\n    46→`make install` builds all three binaries (`cloche`, `cloched`, `cloche-agent`),\n    47→builds the `cloche-agent:latest` Docker image, installs the host binaries to\n    48→`~/.local/bin/`, and starts the daemon. You can change the install prefix:\n    49→\n    50→```\n    51→make install PREFIX=/usr/local\n    52→```\n    53→\n    54→Make sure the install prefix is on your `PATH`:\n    55→\n    56→```\n    57→export PATH=\"$HOME/.local/bin:$PATH\"\n    58→```\n    59→\n    60→## `go install`\n    61→\n    62→If you have Go installed, you can install the host binaries directly:\n    63→\n    64→```\n    65→go install github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/cmd/cloche@latest\n    66→go install github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/cmd/cloched@latest\n    67→```\n    68→\n    69→This places the binaries in `$GOPATH/bin` (or `$HOME/go/bin` by default).\n    70→\n    71→**Important:** You must also build the Docker image — Cloche cannot run\n    72→workflows without it. Clone the repository and run:\n    73→\n    74→```\n    75→git clone https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche.git\n    76→cd cloche\n    77→make docker-build\n    78→```\n    79→\n    80→## Pre-built Release Binaries\n    81→\n    82→> **Planned** — Pre-built release binaries are not yet available. This section\n    83→> describes the intended installation method once GitHub Releases are set up.\n    84→\n    85→Download pre-built binaries from the GitHub Releases page. Each release will\n    86→include archives for Linux amd64, Linux arm64, macOS amd64, and macOS arm64.\n    87→\n    88→```\n    89→# Example: Linux amd64\n    90→curl -LO https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/releases/latest/download/cloche-linux-amd64.tar.gz\n    91→tar xzf cloche-linux-amd64.tar.gz\n    92→sudo install cloche cloched /usr/local/bin/\n    93→```\n    94→\n    95→You still need to build the Docker image. Clone the repo and run\n    96→`make docker-build`.\n    97→\n    98→## Homebrew (macOS / Linux)\n    99→\n   100→> **Planned** — A Homebrew tap is not yet published. This section describes the\n   101→> intended installation method once the tap is available.\n   102→\n   103→```\n   104→brew tap cloche-dev/tap\n   105→brew install cloche\n   106→```\n   107→\n   108→This will install the host binaries (`cloche` and `cloched`). You still need\n   109→the Docker image — the formula will print post-install instructions for building\n   110→it.\n   111→\n   112→## Verifying the Installation\n   113→\n   114→After installing, verify that everything works:\n   115→\n   116→```\n   117→# Check the binaries\n   118→cloche --help\n   119→cloched --help\n   120→\n   121→# Start the daemon (if not already running)\n   122→cloched &\n   123→\n   124→# Ensure the agent Docker image exists\n   125→docker images cloche-agent:latest\n   126→\n   127→# Run a quick test from any git repository with a .cloche/ directory\n   128→cloche list\n   129→```\n   130→\n   131→## Upgrading\n   132→\n   133→To upgrade an existing installation, repeat your original installation method.\n   134→If you built from source:\n   135→\n   136→```\n   137→cd cloche\n   138→git pull\n   139→make install\n   140→```\n   141→\n   142→The `make install` target stops the running daemon, installs the new binaries,\n   143→rebuilds the Docker image, and restarts the daemon automatically.\n   144→\n   145→## Next Steps\n   146→\n   147→- [Usage guide](USAGE.md) — quick start, CLI reference, and workflow setup\n   148→- [Workflow DSL reference](workflows.md) — full syntax for `.cloche` files\n   149→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f3aa3a38-ba4f-483d-b376-7f0377d12dcf","uuid":"0e9ca374-d3e1-48b0-a5a0-696d015d3dcf","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/INSTALL.md","content":"# Installation\n\nThis document covers the various ways to install Cloche on your machine.\n\n## Prerequisites\n\nAll installation methods require:\n\n- **Docker** — Cloche runs workflows in containers\n- **Git** — result extraction uses git worktrees\n- **`ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`** — for agent steps using Claude Code\n\nFor building from source, you also need:\n\n- **Go 1.25.3+** — matching the version in `go.mod`\n\nNote: Node.js and npm are only needed *inside* the container image (for Claude\nCode). You do **not** need to install them on the host — the Docker image build\nhandles this automatically.\n\n## Architecture: What Runs Where\n\nUnderstanding which components run on the host vs inside containers helps\nclarify what you need to install:\n\n| Component | Where it runs | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| `cloche` (CLI) | Host | Sends commands to the daemon over gRPC |\n| `cloched` (Daemon) | Host | Manages container lifecycle and state |\n| `cloche-agent` | Inside containers only | Built into the `cloche-agent:latest` Docker image |\n\nYou only need `cloche` and `cloched` on your host. The `cloche-agent` binary is\ncompiled into the Docker image during `make docker-build` and never needs to be\ninstalled on the host.\n\n## Build from Source\n\nClone the repository, build the binaries and Docker image, and install them:\n\n```\ngit clone https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche.git\ncd cloche\nmake install\n```\n\n`make install` builds all three binaries (`cloche`, `cloched`, `cloche-agent`),\nbuilds the `cloche-agent:latest` Docker image, installs the host binaries to\n`~/.local/bin/`, and starts the daemon. You can change the install prefix:\n\n```\nmake install PREFIX=/usr/local\n```\n\nMake sure the install prefix is on your `PATH`:\n\n```\nexport PATH=\"$HOME/.local/bin:$PATH\"\n```\n\n## `go install`\n\nIf you have Go installed, you can install the host binaries directly:\n\n```\ngo install github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/cmd/cloche@latest\ngo install github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/cmd/cloched@latest\n```\n\nThis places the binaries in `$GOPATH/bin` (or `$HOME/go/bin` by default).\n\n**Important:** You must also build the Docker image — Cloche cannot run\nworkflows without it. Clone the repository and run:\n\n```\ngit clone https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche.git\ncd cloche\nmake docker-build\n```\n\n## Pre-built Release Binaries\n\n> **Planned** — Pre-built release binaries are not yet available. This section\n> describes the intended installation method once GitHub Releases are set up.\n\nDownload pre-built binaries from the GitHub Releases page. Each release will\ninclude archives for Linux amd64, Linux arm64, macOS amd64, and macOS arm64.\n\n```\n# Example: Linux amd64\ncurl -LO https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/releases/latest/download/cloche-linux-amd64.tar.gz\ntar xzf cloche-linux-amd64.tar.gz\nsudo install cloche cloched /usr/local/bin/\n```\n\nYou still need to build the Docker image. Clone the repo and run\n`make docker-build`.\n\n## Homebrew (macOS / Linux)\n\n> **Planned** — A Homebrew tap is not yet published. This section describes the\n> intended installation method once the tap is available.\n\n```\nbrew tap cloche-dev/tap\nbrew install cloche\n```\n\nThis will install the host binaries (`cloche` and `cloched`). You still need\nthe Docker image — the formula will print post-install instructions for building\nit.\n\n## Verifying the Installation\n\nAfter installing, verify that everything works:\n\n```\n# Check the binaries\ncloche --help\ncloched --help\n\n# Start the daemon (if not already running)\ncloched &\n\n# Ensure the agent Docker image exists\ndocker images cloche-agent:latest\n\n# Run a quick test from any git repository with a .cloche/ directory\ncloche list\n```\n\n## Upgrading\n\nTo upgrade an existing installation, repeat your original installation method.\nIf you built from source:\n\n```\ncd cloche\ngit pull\nmake install\n```\n\nThe `make install` target stops the running daemon, installs the new binaries,\nrebuilds the Docker image, and restarts the daemon automatically.\n\n## Next Steps\n\n- [Usage guide](USAGE.md) — quick start, CLI reference, and workflow setup\n- [Workflow DSL reference](workflows.md) — full syntax for `.cloche` files\n","numLines":149,"startLine":1,"totalLines":149}}}
